args: It should be right over... Oh, noice!
Here we go, Ria. That right there\nis what I wanted to show you!
Listen close, children, as I spin a tale\nof the legendary Queen Nefaria!
Fie, these mummers are capering about\nperforming a play of my exploits!
Us dunefolk grow up hearing stories about\nyou! That's how the kids we bumped into\nknew your name.
Uh, you still with me, girl?\nYou kinda locked up there.
I'm merely a bit...trepidatious of how\nthis retelling might portray me.
I am the last queen of the Sandreach.\nWhat if I play not the part of the hero, but\nthe mooncalf who led her kingdom to ruin?
Okay, do you SERIOUSLY think I would\nhaul you out here just so some rando\ncould open the library and read you?
Long ago and longer still,\ncenturies before centuries past...
Far to the south, at the vast desert's heart,\nancestors of dunefolk like you and me\nlived in a kingdom called the Sandreach.

Since time immemorial, the Sandreach had been
guided by a royal line that wielded powerful
magics—and the kindest, strongest, and most
beautiful of them all was the last of her line,
good Queen Nefaria.
Not before or since has a ruler cared more for her\npeople; her singular purpose was to see that the\ndunefolk might live happy and free.
When her retainers brought word that her subjects\nwere struggling, she would go to them herself,\nlisten to their worries, and see the issue resolved.
Thus did her people live in peace, secure in the\nknowledge their beloved queen would ever race\nto their aid in times of strife.
And that's the end of chapter one, kids.\nWe'll have a brief break, then continue our\ntale of Queen Nefaria's heroic exploits!
See? You sound like a boss in this story!\nAll the kids are obsessed with you.
Spoiler alert: Basically all us dunefolk\nlove you to bits, Ria.
This is good hearing; I dared not dream\nmy people's line held such love for me.
Dear Nadine, you've my gratitude for\nbringing me to see such a splendid show.\nI am powerfully moved.
Aw, I'm just happy you're happy!
Uh oh. What's up? Did the writer dude\nget something wrong? I'll give notes!
To hear such unvarnished praise is a\nticklish thing. Surely even the most\nshameless flattery must have limits!
I've vague recollections of leaving the\npalace to speak with subjects, but these\nclaims of racing to their side...

But you DID talk to them, right? I mean,
that's proof enough you cared, 'cause most
royal folk just sit in their castle and eat
big turkey legs all day or whatever.
And so what if they talked you up a bit\nto the grandkids? That's just proof of\nhow much they loved you!
Then you would hold this flattery\nto be born of affection true?
A pretty thought, if it be so.\nI suppose I ought not spurn it,\nthough it belies the facts.
Gather 'round and listen to the second part\nof our tale of good Queen Nefaria!
The great queen was more than just a kind ruler:\nShe was also a sorceress of tremendous power!
When seas roiled and the people could not sail,\nthey besought their queen for aid. So wise Nefaria\ncast a mighty bolt into the depths...
And the vast sea was split in twain, allowing her\nsubjects to load their wares on carts and cross\nthe bare seabed to trade with other lands!

But Nefaria was more than powerful: Her beauty
was unmatched in all the world! Her wardrobe
teemed with garbs of finest silk, and the sight of
her dressed in resplendent finery filled her people
with much hope and pride.
Whenever she donned a new dress and danced,\nall who witnessed her fell instantly in love. Why,\neven a dragon once begged her hand in marriage!
Kindness, might, and beauty—the legendary queen\nhad all these things and more. And so we sing the\npraises of Nefaria, pride of the desert sands!
Yaaaay, good Queen Nefaria!\nGo ON with your bad self!
I stand transfixed at this story...\nI haven't even the words at hand!
A mirthless jest, Nadine; I am aghast!
Whaaat?! Wait, why?! I thought we\ndecided a little embellishment was\njust a sign of love.
All things have their limit, and those tales\nheld nary a whiff of truth. Fie, but each\nclaim was more fanciful than the last!
So they didn't just...you know?\nTell a true story with a little extra spice?
Perhaps where spellcraft was concerned;\n'tis sooth the royal line e'er possessed\nmagics most potent.
But these claims of my...my BEAUTY\nare entirely spurious!
This mad prattle of dragons enamored by\nflashy garb and dancing are naught but\nthe most flagrant of fabrications.
And pray tell, from whence has all this talk\nof fashion come? I've never expressed one\nwhit of interest in clo...
Hold. Clothing and dance? Clothing and...\nMarry, why does that sound familiar?!
Ohmigosh, maybe you've got more\nmemories coming back!
Clothing and dance...\nDonning a new dress...
